Here's a real-time example of the observer pattern:

## Scenario: Build State Observer

**Extension A: Build Runner** (emits events)
```typescript
export const buildRunner = {
  name: 'build-runner',

  async runBuild() {
    pi.events.emit('build:start', { timestamp: Date.now() });

    try {
      await this.compile();
      pi.events.emit('build:phase', { phase: 'compile' });

      await this.test();
      pi.events.emit('build:phase', { phase: 'test' });

      pi.events.emit('build:complete', { success: true });
    } catch (error) {
      pi.events.emit('build:error', { error: error.message });
    }
  }
};
```

**Extension B: UI Notifier** (observes events)

```typescript
export const uiNotifier = {
  name: 'ui-notifier',

  register() {
    // Observer pattern: react to state changes
    pi.events.on('build:start', () => showBuildModal());
    pi.events.on('build:phase', ({ phase }) => updateProgress(phase));
    pi.events.on('build:complete', () => hideModal());
    pi.events.on('build:error', ({ error }) => showError(error));
  }
};
```

**Extension C: Logger** (also observes)

```typescript
export const logger = {
  name: 'logger',

  register() {
    pi.events.on('build:start', () => log('Build started'));
    pi.events.on('build:complete', ({ success }) => log(`Build ${success ? 'succeeded' : 'failed'}`));
  }
};
```
